Question 1

A sales company surveyed \(50\) of its employees in order to determine the factors that influence sales performance. Two collections of variables were measured. The first set related to sales performance

  • Sales Growth
  • Sales Profitability
  • New Account Sales

The second set of variables are test scores measuring intelligence:

  • Creativity
  • Mechanical Reasoning
  • Abstract Reasoning
  • Mathematics

You can download the data set sales.csv from Moodle. The following analysis is carried out in R.

dat=read.csv(file='sales2.csv', sep=',',header=TRUE)
X = dat |> dplyr::select('growth', 'profit', 'new') 
Y = dat |> dplyr::select(-'growth', -'profit', -'new')

library(CCA)
cc.out <- cc(X,Y)
print(cc.out$cor)
[1] 0.9944827 0.8781065 0.3836057
print(cc.out$xcoef)

The following gives the correlation between the original variables and the transformed variables

  • Describe the first pair of canonical variables, give their correlation, and provide an interpretation.

  • Describe the second pair of canonical variables, and provide an interpretation.

Solution
  • The first pair of canonical variables is \[\eta_1= -0.062 \times \mbox{Growth} -0.0209 \times \mbox{Profit}-0.078 \times \mbox{new}\] and \[\psi_1 = -0.0697 \times \mbox{create}-0.03 \times \mbox{mech}-0.090 \times \mbox{abs}-0.063 \times \mbox{math}\]

The correlation between \(\eta_1\) (the transformed scales variable) and \(\psi_1\) (the transformed test scores variable) is very high at 0.994.

To interpret the variables, note that \[{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_1, \mbox{growth}) = -0.98, \quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_1, \mbox{profit}) = -0.95,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_1, \mbox{new}) = -0.95\]

These correlations are all uniformly large. Therefore, you can think of this canonical variate as an overall measure of Sales Performance.

\[{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_1, \mbox{create}) = -0.68, \quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_1, \mbox{mech}) = -0.72,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_1, \mbox{abs}) = -0.64,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_1, \mbox{math}) = -0.94\] Because all correlations are large, \(\psi_1\) can be thought of as an overall measure of test performance. It is most strongly correlated with the mathematics test scores.

Because the first canonical correlation is very high (0.99), we can see that the correlations between each set of variables and the opposite group of canonical variates is also high. So

\[{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_1, \mbox{create}) = -0.63, \quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_1, \mbox{mech}) = -0.72,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_1, \mbox{abs}) = -0.64,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_1, \mbox{math}) = -0.94\]

\[{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_1, \mbox{growth}) = -0.97, \quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_1, \mbox{profit}) = -0.94,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_1, \mbox{new}) = -0.95\] For the second set of canonical variables, note that the correlation between the original variables and the transformed variables is low.

\[{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_2, \mbox{growth}) =0.0006, \quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_2, \mbox{profit}) = 0.322,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\eta_2, \mbox{new}) = -0.186\]

\[{\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_2, \mbox{create}) = -0.22, \quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_2, \mbox{mech}) = 0.24,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_2, \mbox{abs}) = -0.50,\quad {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{or}}(\psi_2, \mbox{math}) = 0.20\] So it there isn’t really a meaningful interpretation that can be given.

Question 2

Attempt exam question 1 part (b) from the 2017-18 exam paper:

Solution

This is all bookwork material from the notes.

  1. Put \(\mathbf u=\mathbf S_{xx}^{1/2}\mathbf a\) and \(\mathbf v=\mathbf S_{yy}^{1/2}\mathbf b\). Then \(\mathbf a=\mathbf S_{xx}^{-1/2}\mathbf u\) and \(\mathbf b=\mathbf S_{yy}^{-1/2}\mathbf v\). This transforms eq. (1) into

\[\max_{\mathbf u, \mathbf v} \mathbf u^\top \mathbf S_{xx}^{-1/2}\mathbf S_{xy}\mathbf S_{yy}^{-1/2}\mathbf v\mbox{ subject to } \mathbf u^\top\mathbf u=\mathbf v^\top\mathbf v=1\] i.e., we have \(\mathbf A=\mathbf S_{xx}^{-1/2}\mathbf S_{xy}\mathbf S_{yy}^{-1/2}\).

  1. \(\xi_1, \xi_2, \ldots\) are the canonical correlations. \(\xi_1\) is the largest correlation possible between any linear combination of the x-variables and any linear combination of the y-variables. Subsequent \(\xi_i\) are the largest correlation between additional linear combinations, subject to them being uncorrelated with earlier variables. We have that \(0\leq \xi_i\leq 1\) with \(\xi_1\geq \xi_2\geq \ldots\).

  2. If \(\xi_i=0\) for all \(i\), we would conclude that all possible linear correlations of \(\mathbf x\) and \(\mathbf y\) are uncorrelated. We can see that this only occurs in the SVD when \(\mathbf S_{xy}\) is the \(p \times q\) matrix of zeros.

If \(\xi_i=1\) for all \(i\), this indicates perfect correlation between the \(\mathbf x\)-variables and the \(\mathbf y\)-variables. In the next question, we will see that this happens if \(\mathbf y=\mathbf T\mathbf x\) for some orthogonal matrix \(\mathbf T\).

Question 3

Suppose that \(\mathbf z= (\mathbf x^\top \mathbf y^\top)^\top\) is a random vector, where both \(\mathbf x\) and \(\mathbf y\) are sub-vectors of dimension \(p\), so that \(\mathbf z\) is \((2p)\times 1\). Define \[{\mathbb{V}\operatorname{ar}}(\mathbf z)=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf z\mathbf z}=\begin{pmatrix} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x} & \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf y}\\\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf x} & \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y} \end{pmatrix}.\]

  1. Suppose that \(\mathbf y= \mathbf T\mathbf x\) where \(\mathbf T\) is a fixed matrix. Find \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf y}\) and \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}\) in terms of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\) and \(\mathbf T\).
Solution

We have \[ \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf y}=\text{Cov}(\mathbf x, \mathbf y) =\text{Cov}(\mathbf x, \mathbf T\mathbf x)=\text{Cov}(\mathbf x, \mathbf x)\mathbf T^\top =\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\mathbf T^\top, \] and \[ \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}=\text{Var}(\mathbf T\mathbf x)=\mathbf T\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\mathbf T^\top. \]

  1. Assuming now that \(\mathbf T\) is an orthogonal matrix and \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\) is of full rank, determine the singular values of the matrix \(\mathbf Q=\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}^{-1/2}\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_ {\mathbf x\mathbf y}\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}^{-1/2}\), and hence write down the canonical correlation coefficients.
Solution

Write the spectral decomposition of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\) as \[ \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda\mathbf U^\top. \] Then, since \(\mathbf T\) is an orthogonal matrix, the spectral decomposition of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}\) is given by \[ \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}=\mathbf T\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda\mathbf U^\top \mathbf T^\top=(\mathbf T\mathbf U)\boldsymbol \Lambda(\mathbf T\mathbf U)^\top, \] because \(\mathbf U\) and \(\mathbf T\), and hence \(\mathbf T\mathbf U\), are orthogonal matrices; so the eigenvalues of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}\) are the same as those of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\), and the corresponding matrix of unit eigenvectors of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}\) is given by \(\mathbf T\mathbf U\). Therefore the inverse matrix square roots of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\) and \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}\) are, respectively, \[ \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}^{-1/2}=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2} \mathbf U^\top \quad \hbox{and} \quad \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}^{-1/2}=\mathbf T\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2} (\mathbf T\mathbf U)^\top. \] Consequently, assuming that all the eigenvalues of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\) are strictly positive, \[\begin{align*} \mathbf Q& =\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}^{-1/2}\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf y} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}^{-1/2}\\ &=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2}\mathbf U^\top \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\mathbf T^\top \mathbf T\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2} \mathbf U^\top \mathbf T^\top\\ &=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2}\mathbf U^\top \mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda\mathbf U^\top \mathbf T^\top \mathbf T\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2} \mathbf U^\top \mathbf T^\top\\ &=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2}\boldsymbol \Lambda\boldsymbol \Lambda^{-1/2}\mathbf U^\top \mathbf T^\top\\ &=\mathbf T^\top. \end{align*}\] We now use the SVD (see Result 2.13 in Chapter 2) to obtain \[ \mathbf Q=\mathbf T^\top= \mathbf I_p \mathbf I_p \mathbf T^\top = \sum_{j=1}^p \mathbf e_j {\mathbf t}_j^\top, \] where \(\mathbf e_j\) is the \(j\)th column of \(\mathbf I_p\) and \({\mathbf t}_j\) is the \(j\)th column of \(\mathbf T\). So in this case the canonical correlation coefficients are all equal to \(1\), i.e. the set of \(x\)-variables and the set of \(y\)-variables are, in this sense, perfectly correlated.

  1. Suppose now that \(\mathbf T\) is non-singular but not orthogonal. Comment on whether the answer to part (b) changes.
Solution

Yes, the answer changes if \(\mathbf T\) is not an orthogonal matrix because then the eigenvalues of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf y\mathbf y}\) will differ from those of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{\mathbf x\mathbf x}\) and the two sets of variables will not be perfectly correlated, as happens in part (b).

Question 4

We will now prove Proposition 5.3 by induction. The case for \(k=1\) was proved in Section 5.1 in Proposition 3.9. Assume the result is true for \(k\). Consider the objective \[\mathcal{L} = \mathbf a^\top \mathbf Q\mathbf b+ \sum_{i=1}^k \gamma_i\mathbf a^\top \mathbf a_i + \sum_{i=1}^k \mu_i\mathbf b^\top \mathbf b_i + \frac{\lambda_1}{2}(1-\mathbf a^\top\mathbf a)+ \frac{\lambda_2}{2}(1-\mathbf b^\top\mathbf b)\] where \(\lambda_i, \mu_i, \gamma_i\) are Lagrangian multipliers.

  1. By differentiating with respect to \(\mathbf a\) and \(\mathbf b\) and setting the derivative to zero show that

\[ \mathbf Q\mathbf b+ \sum\gamma_i \mathbf a_i - \lambda_1 \mathbf a= 0 \tag{1}\]

\[\mathbf Q^\top\mathbf a+ \sum\mu_i \mathbf b_i - \lambda_2 \mathbf b= 0. \tag{2}\]

Solution

\[\frac{d\mathcal{L}}{d\mathbf a} = \mathbf Q\mathbf b+\sum_{i=1}^k \gamma_i\mathbf a_i -\lambda_1\mathbf a\] \[\frac{d\mathcal{L}}{d\mathbf b} = \mathbf Q^\top \mathbf a+\sum_{i=1}^k \mu_i\mathbf b_i -\lambda_2\mathbf b\] Setting these equal to zero (as the derivatives will be zero at the maximum) gives the required equations.

  1. By left multiplying the equations above by \(\mathbf a^\top\) and \(\mathbf b^\top\) respectively show that \[\lambda_1=\lambda_2 = \mathbf a^\top \mathbf Q\mathbf b.\]
Solution

\[0=\mathbf a^\top(\mathbf Q\mathbf b+\sum_{i=1}^k \gamma_i\mathbf a_i -\lambda_1\mathbf a) = \mathbf a^\top\mathbf Q\mathbf b+\sum_{i=1}^k \gamma_i\mathbf a^\top\mathbf a_i -\lambda_1\mathbf a^\top\mathbf a= \mathbf a^\top\mathbf Q\mathbf b-\lambda_1 \] as \(\mathbf a^\top\mathbf a=1\) and \(\mathbf a^\top \mathbf a_i=0\). Thus \(\lambda_1 = \mathbf a^\top \mathbf Q\mathbf b\) as required. Similarly for \(\lambda_2\).

  1. By left multiplying (Equation 1) by \(\mathbf a_i^\top\) show that \(\gamma_i=0\) for \(i=1, \ldots, k\). Show similarly that \(\mu_i =0\) for \(i=1, \ldots, k\).
Solution

\[0=\mathbf a_i^\top(\mathbf Q\mathbf b+\sum_{i=1}^k \gamma_i\mathbf a_i -\lambda_1\mathbf a) = \mathbf a_i^\top\mathbf Q\mathbf b+\sum_{i=j}^k \gamma_j\mathbf a_i^\top\mathbf a_j -\lambda_1\mathbf a_i^\top\mathbf a= \mathbf a_i^\top\mathbf Q\mathbf b+\gamma_i \] But \(\mathbf Q=\sum_{j} \sigma_j \mathbf u_j \mathbf v_j^\top\) and \(\mathbf a_i = \mathbf u_i\) and thus \[\mathbf a_i^\top\mathbf Q\mathbf b= \sigma_i \mathbf v_i^\top\mathbf b= \sigma_i\mathbf b_i^\top \mathbf b= 0\] as \(\mathbf v_i=\mathbf b_i\). Thus \(\gamma_i=0\). Similarly \(\mu_i=0\).

  1. Finally, by copying the proof of Proposition 3.9, prove Proposition 5.3.
Solution

We have shown \(\lambda_1\mathbf a= \mathbf Q\mathbf b\) and \(\lambda_1\mathbf b= \mathbf Q^\top \mathbf a\). Substituting one equation into the other, gives \[\mathbf Q\mathbf Q^\top \mathbf a= \lambda_1^2\mathbf a\] So \(\mathbf a\) is an eigenvalue of \(\mathbf Q\mathbf Q^\top\) and so \(\mathbf a=\mathbf u_i\) for some \(i\), and \(\lambda_1=\mathbf a^\top\mathbf Q\mathbf b=\sigma_i\). We know we can’t pick \(i=1, \ldots, k\) by the orthogonality constraints, and so we pick the next largest possible singular value, and let \(\mathbf a=\mathbf u_{k+1}, \mathbf b=\mathbf b_{k+1}\) and then \[\mathbf u_{k+1}^\top \mathbf Q\mathbf b_{k+1} =\sigma_{k+1}.\]

Then by induction we have proven the result.

Question 5

Show the mean of the cc variables \(\eta_k\) and \(\psi_k\) is zero. Prove Proposition 5.4 giving the variance of covariance the canonical correlation variables.

Solution

\[\eta_k=\mathbf a_k^\top (\mathbf x- \bar{\mathbf x})\] Thus \[{\mathbb{E}}\eta_k={\mathbb{E}}(\mathbf a_k^\top (\mathbf x- \bar{\mathbf x})) = \mathbf a_k^\top ({\mathbb{E}}\mathbf x- \bar{\mathbf x})=0\] as required. Similarly for \(\psi_k\).

\[\begin{align*} {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{ov}}(\eta_j, \eta_k) &= {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{ov}}(\mathbf a_j^\top(\mathbf x-\bar{\mathbf x}), \mathbf a_k^\top(\mathbf x-\bar{\mathbf x}))\\ &=\mathbf a_j^\top \mathbf S_{xx}\mathbf a_k\\ &=\mathbf u_j^\top \mathbf S_{xx}^{-1/2}\mathbf S_{xx}\mathbf S_{xx}^{-1/2}\mathbf u_k\\ &=\mathbf u_j^\top \mathbf u_k\\ &=\begin{cases}1\mbox{ if } j=k\\ 0 \mbox{ otherwise.} \end{cases} \end{align*}\] Similarly for \({\mathbb{C}\operatorname{ov}}(\psi_j, \psi_k)\).

\[\begin{align*} {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{ov}}(\eta_j, \psi_k) &= {\mathbb{C}\operatorname{ov}}(\mathbf a_j^\top(\mathbf x-\bar{\mathbf x}), \mathbf b_k^\top(\mathbf y-\bar{\mathbf y}))\\ &=\mathbf a_j^\top \mathbf S_{xy}\mathbf b_k\\ &=\mathbf u_j^\top \mathbf S_{xx}^{-1/2}\mathbf S_{xy}\mathbf S_{yy}^{-1/2}\mathbf v_k\\ &=\mathbf u_j^\top \mathbf Q\mathbf v_k\\ &=\mathbf u_j^\top \left(\sum_i \sigma_i \mathbf u_i \mathbf v_i^\top\right)\mathbf v_k\\ &=\begin{cases}\sigma_j\mbox{ if } j=k\\ 0 \mbox{ otherwise.} \end{cases} \end{align*}\]
